the last character response should match the "vibe" given that the dataset _should_ represent the ideal conversation. We are currently working on enhancements to the overall evaluation and will release more details once that is ready
But it is impossible to train a model to match the vibe when it sees unknown conversations. Currently to get hight vibe score model has to learn the evaluation dataset.
On the other hand, if the model has to match "vibe" of user's messages, then it's completely possible to train such model.

the "vibe" is designed to be a byproduct of the tuning rather than a specific target. as mentioned, we are aware of the limitations of the current evaluation process and are cooking a better system which we will announce once its ready

messages.content:
Providing some clarity on points mentioned earlier in this channel:

Given that it has been nearly a quarter since the launch of dTAO, there have been significant changes to how the team has been able to manage operations on this subnet. I want to highlight the basis of why we are building on the subnet in the first place as I believe that this will provide clarity on what is prioritized and healthy to the subnet as a whole.
First, let's consider the general goal of this subnet. Unlike some other subnets, the output of this subnet is a public good - namely an open source LLM that is _good_ at roleplay.
Now that dTAO is involved, there are some additional dynamics that impact the efficacy of this goal and how it might compete against the bittensor ecosystem. 
Without getting into deep details, this subnet's thesis is this: the Dippy app is one of the few large scale consumer apps utilizing AI (with millions of users), and the subnet directly drives this growth by producing better models.

That brings us to the next question: how can a better model be developed? This is where challenges start to appear. There are two simple but difficult goals to accomplish: having a strong dataset to train on, and having an effective evaluation method.
The first point is rarely on anyone's mind because anyone who is not truly dedicated to the improvement of models doesn't care. What most people don't know is that the Dippy team has developed our own dataset at our own cost (thousands of dollars a month) to provide a quality synthetic dataset for training (that is continuously generated!). If you spend even 10 minutes on what datasets are available, you will see that there is a lack of high quality, high quantity datasets for roleplay. That being said, we are always looking to make improvements to this dataset and changes here are critical. This is one basis to the frequency of scoring resets and how we are always improving the base quality of the subnet.

The next goal is just as challenging, if not more so. Today, popular evaluation methods consist of benchmarks and sometimes statistical evaluation. On a subnet, popular benchmarks (ie MMLU, lmarena, etc) are not suited given their static nature and the ever looming challenge of training on benchmark data. This is also compounded by the fact that the current popular method today of reasoning does not directly apply to roleplay (RL for example is based on objective truth, which is not a desired property of roleplay models). Our current approach to this is the judge score, and the conviction on this is strong enough to make this the only metric to utilize in this current scoring epoch. That being said, it is not the only optimal method of scoring. In the past, models that have scored well on the leaderboard have failed to provide strong enough engagement in the Dippy app. While a large part of this is on us as we are responsible for the evaluation method, our own analysis of miner submitted models (all of them, not just the top scoring ones) have yielded the fact that most are negligible improvements over base models. There are ways to improve this, especially given Dippy’s position of garnering feedback from millions of users. However, to do so as openly as possible is limiting. For one, there is the consideration of user privacy in chat messages. While we have a pipeline developing for this, it is not an easy task. Another method would be to directly pit models against each other in the Dippy app, but again the structure of the subnet (and the fact that there are 200+ entries) provides logistical challenges. Companies producing proprietary models are much less accountable in this respect.

On top of these factors, the bittensor subnet structure severely limits what can be done in regards to tokenomics. If there was the option to burn validator or even subnet owner emissions, we would have done so happily. However, OTF has only allowed for miner emissions to be burned. It’s honestly embarrassing to consider that there is not even an official burn address available that many other chains have implemented. I’m sure there are reasons for this, but what stands today is that there is a strong limitation on how subnets can be operated. (In fact, I have my own ideas on how to approach this, but this is outside of the scope of this subnet specifically). All this to say that the definition of a “good model” is always moving and that once a promising model results in stronger engagement inside Dippy, there will be clearer guidelines for miners. This is not to say that all models have been bad: it has only been a few months since we drastically improved the quality of the models, but we want only the best for Dippy.

Despite all of these challenges, we believe in the potential of bittensor and are still committed, if not more, to this endeavor. We have not sold any subnet tokens, and the burn is only there to manage the dynamics of dTAO given the few controls we have.
